Use MAUI's `Window` lifecycle events — `Backgrounding` and `Resumed` — combined with `Preferences` for lightweight persistence:

```csharp
// In your App.xaml.cs
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) =>
    {
        // Save draft when app goes to background
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
        {
            Preferences.Set("draft_note", page.GetDraftText());
        }
    };

    window.Resumed += (s, e) =>
    {
        // Restore draft when app returns
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
        {
            var draft = Preferences.Get("draft_note", string.Empty);
            if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(draft))
                page.SetDraftText(draft);
        }
    };

    return window;
}
```

```csharp
// In NotePage.xaml.cs
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    public string GetDraftText() => NoteEditor.Text ?? string.Empty;

    public void SetDraftText(string text) => NoteEditor.Text = text;
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`Backgrounding`** fires when the app loses focus (home button, app switch). Save here — not in `Stopped`, which may not fire.
- **`Resumed`** fires when the app returns to the foreground.
- **`Preferences`** is ideal for small text. For larger content, use `SecureStorage` or write to `FileSystem.AppDataDirectory`.
- Clear the draft after the user explicitly saves: `Preferences.Remove("draft_note")`.
